								h3 How do I start scanning?
								p Scanning with PT BBS is fast and easy. Just enter the address of your site—on the internet or a local network—and configure your scanning method:
								.readmore__inner
									.readmore__hidden-text.js-read-more-hidden-text
										.readmore__hidden-text-inner
											ul
												li Without confirmation of site ownership, you can scan via an agent. An agent is a small program that can be run without local installation—just open a secure executable file and you can start scanning. This is a convenient method when you cannot or do not want to make alterations to your site's root directory, or when your site is located behind a NAT (in a local network). Note that this method does not allow for anonymous scanning. All requests from the agent are tunneled from our service to the site being scanned via the computer of the user who initiated the scanning. This means that the computer (IP address) where the requests originated will be visible on the site side.
												li With confirmation of site ownership. For this method, a special HTML file must be placed in the root directory of the site that you want to scan. Our system will "see" the file and allow scanning to be initiated.
									button.readmore__button.js-readmore-button Show more
							.readmore.js-read-more
								h3 What is an agent and what is it used for? Why might several agents be needed?
								p installation or any special privileges. Agents are needed to scan sites in local networks (behind NATs) and in cases when site ownership cannot be confirmed using a certificate. This occurs, for instance, when an audit is performed by external experts who do not have access to site servers. The agent creates a tunnel to send requests from the server conducting the scan to the site that is being scanned.
								.readmore__inner
									.readmore__hidden-text.js-read-more-hidden-text
										.readmore__hidden-text-inner
											p When scanning via an agent, a corresponding setting must be toggled when initially configuring the scan. The agent must then be launched and activated with a code generated by our service before scanning begins. 
											p It is possible to use multiple agents with a single account. This feature is needed if you plan to scan different sites from different locations, such as from your workplace and home computer, on a local network, or remotely. By default, we try to conduct scans using the most recently downloaded agent. However, if you would like to configure scans of specific sites with specific agents, you can do so in the site's settings.
									button.readmore__button.js-readmore-button Show more
							.readmore.js-read-more
								h3 How can I configure a scan for an area of a site that is only login and password accessible (with required authentication)?
								p Our service supports two types of scanning for authentication-protected sites: HTTP Basic and HTML Form. These can be enabled while selecting scanning parameters for a given site. To do so, mark the "Authentication" checkbox and select the desired scan type:
								.readmore__inner
									.readmore__hidden-text.js-read-more-hidden-text
										.readmore__hidden-text-inner
											ul
												li HTTP Basic authentication will only require the username and password of the user under whose name scanning has been authorized on the site.
												li HTML Form authentication requires the URL of the authorization form and a verification string in addition to the username and password. A verification string is any fragment of text from a page with authorization-controlled access. This text fragment is needed for the scanner to verify successful authorization.
									button.readmore__button.js-readmore-button Show more
							.readmore.js-read-more
